# C# style (FileSystemics)

Follow the repository [.editorconfig](../../.editorconfig) for automated formatting. Run `dotnet format` (or `python3 scripts/reformat-kr.py` for bulk K&R migration) before committing C# changes. These rules apply to all C# in this repository.

## K&R bracing

Opening braces stay on the same line as the statement they belong to.

```csharp
// Good
if (path.IsEmpty) {
    return false;
}

public static bool Exists(ReadOnlySpan<char> path) {
    ...
}

// Bad (Allman)
if (path.IsEmpty)
{
    return false;
}
```

## Explicit types

Do not use `var`. Always declare the explicit type.

```csharp
// Good
string path = GetTempPath();
List<string> results = [];

// Bad
var path = GetTempPath();
var results = new List<string>();
```

## Key-value deconstruction

When iterating key-value pairs, deconstruct in the `foreach` (or assignment). Do not bind a `KeyValuePair<,>` variable.

```csharp
// Good
foreach ((string key, MemoryFileData value) in files) {
    ...
}

// Bad
foreach (KeyValuePair<string, MemoryFileData> entry in files) {
    ...
}
```

Apply the same pattern to tuple returns and other multi-value bindings when the values are used separately.

## String interpolation

Always use string interpolation (`$"..."`) instead of the `+` operator to build strings from literals, variables, or expressions.

```csharp
// Good
string path = $"{directory}{separator}{fileName}";
string message = $"File not found: {path} (errno {errno})";
throw new IOException($"Native error (errno {errno})");

// Bad
string path = directory + separator + fileName;
string message = "File not found: " + path + " (errno " + errno + ")";
```

Use `string.Create`, `StringBuilder`, or `Span<char>` only when you are deliberately avoiding allocations or building incrementally in a hot loop—not as a substitute for simple interpolation.
